1.1 The long-term trend in Homicides in Western Europe

Understanding how homicide rates have changed prior to the modern era requires the help of historians and archivists. Manuel Eisner, a criminology professor at the University of Cambridge, and his colleagues published the Historical Violence Database a compilation of data on long-term trends in homicide rates, in addition to qualitative information such as the cause of death, perpetrator and victim. This database is limited to countries with relatively complete historical records on violence and crime – mainly Western Europe and the US.

Starting in the second half of the nineteenth century, these European regions have consistent police records of those accused of murder or manslaughter and annual counts of homicide victims. To go back further in time, reaching as far back as the thirteenth century, Eisner collected estimates (from historical records of coroner reports, court trials, and the police) of homicide rates made in over ninety publications by scholars.

Homicide rates – measured as the number of homicides per 100,000 individuals – up to 1990 are sourced from Eisner’s (2003) publication and the Historical Violence Database.

Are homicide rates in Europe today lower or higher than in the past? Using the provided dataset, display and describe the long-run homicide rates for the five European regions: Italy, England, Germany, Netherlands and Scandinavia.

1.6 Compare the trends in homicide with the pattern of reign duration among Danish rulers through time.

  • Load your Danish king dataset. Hopefully it is tidy and your years and duration of reign are all numeric.
  • You need to have a consistent way of plotting the rulers’ reign on the x axis, so I recommend you create a midyear column by calculating the middle of each monarch’s rule (Hint: midyear = endyear - (endyear-startyear)/2)
  • Start a ggplot plotting midyear on x axis and duration on y axis
  • Try geom_smooth() for geometry
  • Provide meaningful labels and a title
  • How would you characterize the trend compared to the homicides above?
# YOUR CODE HERE:

#Loading the csv file 

kings <- read_csv(("data/kings.csv") , na=c("NULL", ""))

# Adding duration column to the file

kingsduration <- kings %>% 
  mutate(duration=End_year-Start_year)

# Creating midyear column 
kingsduration <- kingsduration %>%
  mutate(Midyear = Start_year + (End_year - Start_year)/2)

# Creating GGplot without confidence interval
kingsduration %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x= Midyear, y=duration)) +
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Reign duration of Danish Monarchs Over Time",
  y = "Years of reign",
  x = "Year")

1.7.1 Final question:

In <250 words articulate your answer on the basis of the data visualisations to the following question:** are we more civilized today?** (Can you find an article or a book that discusses this topic?)

If we only look at the graph we’re working with in the task then it shows a trend in less homicides. By only using that particular data it could be concluded that we have become more civilized over time, if civilized is defined by less homicides. But the data is not very representative and nuanced as it only shows western european countries. It is not a big coverage considering that I have to decide whether we have become more civilized, generally, which is a big question that needs broader coverage. Besides, homicide should include genocide, wars, the slave trade etc. and clearly the data does not, e.g with the result of World War II, show the genocide of Nazis victims. This article, https://www.goodnewsnetwork.org/global-homicide-rates-continue-to-fall-2020/?fbclid=IwY2xjawI-V3ZleHRuA2FlbQIxMAABHVt1btTXq7iiXsuDbSGYdmGef-zK-u52W8Hddp6vLlWCEhx7EmZfsARxUA_aem_OaYCcqbzukWGqYjzmXAaBg, discusses the drop of homicides and crime and has better representation of countries. Being civilized contains complexity because of other factors such as equality, political stability and human rights. I think it is hard to give a definitive answer whether we are more civilized today. Crimes and homicide may have dropped in western countries compared to for example the Middle Ages but that doesn’t necessarily mean that, that is the case in the rest of the world. Other factors should also play a role in the question of being civilized. The genocides in Gaza and in Congo, the Trump administration and their impact on human rights, especially for women and LGBTQ+ people, and the Russian-Ukrainian conflict makes the world seem uncivilized.
